observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Evaluate the LGU’s current organizational structure and manning complement and consider adding personnel to the Accounting and Treasury Units. Also, require the Municipal Accountant to facilitate or conduct an orientation and/or training for employees and staff assigned to these units;

Review and correct the erroneous practice of the LGU in the issuance of checks and follow the guidelines set in Section 44, Chapter 3 of the LGU NGAS;

Create a team to expedite the submission of delayed accounts for the period March to December 2023, ensuring that these disbursement vouchers are submitted with complete supporting documents on or before January 31, 2024, to avoid issuance of the Notice of Suspensions; and

Observe faithfully the reglementary periods set for the submission of accounts and reports for a prompt audit and early reporting of audit results.

Recommendations:
13.10	We recommended and the Management agreed to:
13.10.1	Strictly adhere to Section 7.0 of the guidelines on the procedures and proper disposition of dormant accounts, given the lack of supporting documents for most of the receivable accounts;
13.10.2	Submit a Request for Write-off to the COA office upon completing the required procedures outlined in the preceding recommendation;
13.10.3	Instruct the Accountant to ensure proper disclosure in the Notes to the Financial Statements on the status and adjustments of the subject receivable accounts; and
13.10.4	For the “Other Receivables” under the Trust Fund, conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the receivables. Additionally, determine the status of the responsible recipients, including whether they are still alive or have been displaced. For those found to be deceased, attach a copy of the death certificate when submitting the Request for Write-off.

We recommended that Management: 

Require the Municipal Development Council and the budget committee to judiciously plan and identify the Programs/Projects/Activities (PPAs) to be funded out of the 20% Development Fund and include only those that are feasible and could be accomplished within the target date of completion; 

Fully implement the programmed development PPAs during the year as embodied in the Annual Investment/Development Plan and ensure optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund for the benefit of the constituents of the Municipality; 

Promptly implement all the PPAs under the continuing appropriation;




Strictly observe proper timelines and install effective monitoring of fund utilization and implementation; and


Ensure that all savings from completed projects and all projects that are no longer feasible and not yet implemented are considered for immediate realignment subject to budgetary rules or reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the 20% Development Fund for re-appropriation to other development projects.

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned LGU officers and inventory committee to finish conducting the annual physical count of PPEs, which includes the Road Network System following the required format prescribed in COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015;
Require the Accounting Office and the Property Custodian to reconcile their respective records regularly for check and balance;
Require the Accounting Office to maintain the subsidiary ledger card for each group of PPEs;
Require the Property Custodian to render a (a) Report on Local Road Network at the end of each accounting period; (b) Local Road Inventory and Road map; and (c) Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components; and
Prioritize / commit to undertaking the cleansing of the PPE account balance pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

